Running uses four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ and full threshold matching.

\subsection{Evaluation scales and trial count}

For each quark we admit its self-scale and any SM particle mass within its perturbative running window. The top quark is held at its self-scale throughout (an operational convention for this scan, reflecting that $m_t$ enters the quoted FLAG/PDG value directly rather than via running, not a statement about the renormalization group). Light quarks $(u, d, s)$ have no perturbative self-scale and are referenced to $2$~GeV as the canonical FLAG scale.

The complete scale list is archived as \texttt{search\_space.json}~\citep{RepoMC}. The audited trial count, with the complete enumeration in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}, is
\begin{equation}
20\;\text{triples} \times 4\;\text{signs} \times (\text{variable scales per triple}) = 12{,}960\;\text{trials.}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Scope and defense of the search space}

The scale set is finite, discrete, and drawn from physically interpretable reference scales appearing in the literature: particle thresholds, SM particle masses, and the canonical FLAG reference at $2$~GeV. Two properties of this choice deserve emphasis.

First, the audit is \emph{non-exhaustive by construction}. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses). Each of these is an extension to which the same methodology could be applied.

Second, the audit is \emph{conservative with respect to scale freedom}. The $p$-values reported here apply only to the enumerated discrete search space; enlarging the scale set to arbitrary or continuous choices would increase the look-elsewhere burden and can only weaken significance claims. The discrete audit is therefore a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting of all conceivable scale freedom.


\section{Observed results}
\label{sec:results}

We write $\sigma_Q$ for the propagated uncertainty on $Q$ from the FLAG/PDG mass uncertainties and $\alpha_s$; it is computed by Monte Carlo resampling in Model~B (Section~\ref{sec:mc}), treating the inputs as Gaussian and uncorrelated in the baseline with correlation sensitivity tested in Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}. Because $Q$ is a nonlinear function of six masses and its sensitivity to each input differs across triples, $\sigma_Q$ is triple-specific; the representative SM-central value $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ is the magnitude that appears in the hit-count threshold and drift discussions below, and the per-triple values used in the Model~B $p$-value computation are those obtained by resampling within each trial. Of the 12{,}960 trials, 8 produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$, distributed across exactly three triples. The expected number of sub-$\sigma$ hits under the parametric bootstrap (Section~\ref{sec:mc}) is approximately~7, so the observed count is consistent with what perturbations of the actual masses would generate.

