\subsection{Loss-bias check on dropped CRunDec draws}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

Approximately $33\%$ of random-spectrum Model~A draws fail to produce valid CRunDec output for running claims (specifically $3{,}269$ of $10{,}000$ in the baseline run); failures occur when the random spectrum produces pathological QCD configurations (charm-bottom thresholds too close, $\alpha_s$ blow-up, etc.). To check whether this loss biases the reported $p$-values, we performed two diagnostics.

\paragraph{Distributional comparison of dropped vs.\ retained draws.} Using the surrogate running scheme, we compared the distribution of best residuals for the dropped draws against the same distribution for the successful draws. The two distributions differ: dropped draws have a median best residual of $8.05 \times 10^{-5}$ versus $5.66 \times 10^{-5}$ for successful draws (ratio $1.42$); a two-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test gives $p_{\text{KS}} \approx 8.5 \times 10^{-26}$. These observations are suggestive of stochastic dominance of the dropped-draw best-residual distribution over the retained-draw distribution, which would imply that excluding the dropped draws biases reported tail probabilities upward (i.e., conservatively). Two caveats prevent us from treating this as a validated conservativeness claim: the comparison routes through the surrogate running scheme that did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), and median/KS evidence does not prove stochastic dominance at the full distributional level.

\paragraph{Engine-switching crosschecks.} As a second diagnostic, we re-ran Model~A using 2-loop CRunDec in place of 4-loop, on paired random-spectrum draws ($N = 10{,}000$). The failure set is identical: the same $3{,}269$ draws fail at both loop orders, and the retained sets coincide. The failures are therefore intrinsic to the pathological mass spectra rather than to loop-order specifics, and alternative loop orders within CRunDec do not reduce the dropout rate or give access to the dropped-draw full-pipeline values.

As a third diagnostic, we re-ran Model~A using a pure-Python analytic 1-loop running scheme (closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching), which has no CRunDec dependency and substantially lower failure rate. This scheme has $13.4\%$ dropout (vs.\ $32.7\%$ for full CRunDec), allowing direct comparison of the full-search Model~A tail probability with and without the bulk of the dropped draws contributing. The result: full-search tail probability $\approx 0.37$ under analytic 1-loop running with $13.4\%$ dropout, versus $\approx 0.50$ under 4-loop CRunDec with $32.7\%$ dropout. The lower-dropout scheme returns a \emph{smaller} tail probability, which is the direction predicted by the conservative-bias conjecture: if the dropped draws have systematically larger best residuals, retaining more of them lowers the median null residual and makes the observed value look less typical (smaller tail probability). This is consistent with the median and KS evidence above and provides independent support for the conservative-direction conjecture, though the comparison is confounded by the difference in loop order between the two schemes (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}).

\paragraph{Summary.} We do not claim that the reported Model~A tail probabilities are exact upper bounds on the true tail probabilities. We report them as values computed on the subset of draws for which full CRunDec succeeds. Three lines of evidence---distributional comparison, engine-switching, and analytic-runner crosscheck---point in the same direction: the dropout exclusion biases reported tail probabilities upward (conservatively) by an amount of order $0.1$ in absolute tail probability for the full-search case. The bias direction is consistent across diagnostics; the absolute magnitude is bounded by the same order as the loop-order systematic discussed in Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}. The qualitative ranking of claims is preserved across all dropout-bias diagnostics.

\subsection{Loop-order dependence of absolute Model~A tail probabilities}
\label{sec:loop-order}

To assess the sensitivity of the absolute Model~A tail probabilities to the perturbative order of the running implementation, we re-ran Model~A at 1-loop, 3-loop, 4-loop, and 5-loop CRunDec on identical paired random-spectrum draws ($N = 10{,}000$). For \emph{self-scale} claims (those evaluated at $\mu = m_i$ without inter-flavor running, including Cao $(c,b,t)$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$, and the chain-no-run and 20-triple self families), the tail probabilities are stable to four decimal places across all loop orders, as expected: these claims do not invoke running across flavor thresholds and the loop-order choice does not change their numerical evaluation.

For \emph{running} claims, there is a real but bounded loop-order spread. The full-search Model~A tail probability returns $\{0.57, 0.63, 0.50, 0.53\}$ at orders $\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$ respectively---a spread of $\approx 0.13$ across four loop orders, with 4-loop and 5-loop closest to each other. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ baseline tail probability returns $\{0.003, 0.005, 0.002, 0.004\}$ at orders $\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$---a spread of $\approx 0.003$, all values within the same order of magnitude and all firmly below $0.01$. The $(c,b,t)$ all-signs-with-running family returns $\{0.010, 0.013, 0.007, 0.013\}$. Across all running claims and across the four-orders set, the qualitative ranking is preserved.

A separate 2-loop CRunDec run gave a full-search tail probability of $\approx 0.04$, which is anomalously far from the 1-loop, 3-loop, 4-loop, and 5-loop values that lie in $[0.50, 0.63]$. The origin of the 2-loop discrepancy is under investigation; the 2-loop run is not used in the main analysis and is reported here only for completeness. The 1/3/4/5-loop convergence pattern shows the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for running claims to be stable at the $\sim 0.05$ level across well-behaved loop orders, which is comparable to the dropout-induced bias bound from Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias} and substantially smaller than the prior-class systematic from Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}. All Model~A numbers reported in the main text and Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} use 4-loop running.



