You are an independent scientific reviewer. Review this manuscript for
methodological correctness. For each error or concern, classify its severity.

SEVERITY CLASSIFICATION (required for every finding):

RETRACTION-WORTHY: The error means the paper's central conclusions CANNOT be
supported by the data as presented. Not "could be improved" — "fundamentally broken."
Examples: data coding errors that change the primary outcome, impossible statistical
values, applying tests that don't match the study design rendering all inferences invalid.

MAJOR-REVISION: A real methodological concern that could change conclusions if
addressed differently, but does NOT definitively invalidate them.
Examples: missing controls, underpowered secondary analyses, questionable but
defensible statistical choices.

MINOR: Valid criticism applicable to most published papers. Would not change conclusions.
Examples: no robustness checks, limited generalizability, minor reporting gaps.

KEY TEST: If confirmed, would this need RETRACTION, REVISION, or just NOTING?

Manuscript:
\documentclass[11pt,a4paper]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb,amsthm}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage[margin=1in]{geometry}
\usepackage{natbib}

\title{Look-elsewhere correction for Koide-type\\quark mass relations}
\author{Andrew M.~Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide combination $Q = (\sum m_i)/(\sum \sqrt{m_i})^2 = 2/3$, observed for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$, has motivated numerous extensions to the quark sector. These extensions typically introduce degrees of freedom not present in the original lepton relation---evaluation at non-self renormalization scales, signed square roots, or selection among multiple quark triples---without a systematic accounting of how each degree of freedom inflates the false-positive rate. This note attempts such an accounting for the quark-only case.

We enumerate 12{,}960 trials over 20 quark triples, four sign assignments, and an audited list of physically interpretable evaluation scales, and apply two complementary tools: Model~A, a random-spectrum reference null with full four-loop CRunDec running on every draw, and Model~B, a local-stability diagnostic computed by parametric bootstrap around the observed FLAG/PDG central values. The two answer different questions and are reported separately; they cannot be combined into a single summary probability. Model~A's tail probabilities are relative rankings within the chosen log-uniform SM-like prior, not absolute significance levels. Model~B's tail probability is approximately a monotone function of $|Q - 2/3| / \sigma_Q$ and carries no additional evidential content beyond that ratio.

At full search freedom (12{,}960 trials, $N = 100{,}000$ Model~A draws of which $\approx 67{,}000$ retain after CRunDec dropout), the observed best closure sits at the centre of the Model~A null distribution (tail probability $\approx 0.50$) and within Model~B measurement-noise perturbations (tail probability $\approx 0.50$). Single-triple claims fixed in prior work have smaller Model~A baseline tail probabilities, in the range $\approx 0.003$--$0.04$: Cao $(c,b,t)$ self-scale at $\approx 0.007$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$ signed-self at $\approx 0.03$, and $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ at $\approx 0.003$ (or $\approx 0.004$--$0.016$ across hierarchy-preserving variants). These absolute values carry several systematics that exceed the Monte Carlo binomial standard error: the prior-class systematic from the choice of log-uniform SM-spanning prior; a loop-order systematic measured by re-running at 1, 3, 4, and 5 loops on identical paired draws (full-search tail probability $\{0.57, 0.63, 0.50, 0.53\}$ across these orders, a spread of $\approx 0.13$; self-scale claims are stable across loop orders to four decimal places; 4-loop is used for all reported numbers); and a dropout systematic from the $\approx 33\%$ CRunDec failure rate, bounded conservatively by an analytic-1-loop crosscheck with $\approx 13\%$ dropout that returns full-search tail probability $\approx 0.37$ (lower than the 4-loop value, in the direction predicted by the conservative-bias conjecture). The Model~A values should be read as within-prior, within-loop-order, within-dropout-condition relative rankings rather than as calibrated significance levels. Within those conditions the qualitative ranking is stable. The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim was formulated by the present author on the same FLAG/PDG central values used in the audit; the audit began as a sanity check on that prior claim before being extended to the full quark-side search. The reported tail probability is therefore a multiplicity-corrected restatement of a prior author claim under the audit's chosen prior class, not an independent confirmation.

A matched-complexity knob-isolation test (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}) at equal trial counts across sign-only, running-only, and combined search pools finds that admitting non-self-scale running shifts the Model~A null-distribution median toward smaller residuals by more than trial-count multiplicity alone accounts for, consistent with a distinct contribution from scale freedom. We additionally tabulate the temporal trajectory of $|Q - 2/3|$ across consecutive FLAG/PDG releases as an independent discriminator: the original lepton Koide residual has tracked decreasing $\sigma_Q$ downward since 1981 (Koide's 1981 prediction $m_\tau = 1776.97$~MeV was confirmed within $0.04\sigma$ by the 1996 BES analysis), while the Rivero and Cao quark-side residuals have remained an order of magnitude or more larger than current $\sigma_Q$ across the past decade of measurement updates.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Koide~\citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} observed that the charged lepton pole masses satisfy
\begin{equation}
Q(e, \mu, \tau) \;\equiv\; \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} \;=\; \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide}
\end{equation}
to a residual of $6.2 \times 10^{-6}$. Extensions of this relation to the quark sector include Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for $(s, c, b)$ with signed $\sqrt{m_s}$; Rodejohann and Zhang~\citep{RZ2011} surveying multiple triples; Cao~\citep{Cao2012} for $(c, b, t)$ at self-scales; and Brilliant~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} for $(c, b, t)$ with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$.

Each such extension introduces one or more degrees of freedom relative to the original formula: which triple, which sign pattern for the square roots, which evaluation scale for each mass. The question this note addresses is the standard look-elsewhere question~\citep{GrossVitells2010}: \emph{given the degrees of freedom employed, how often would random or perturbed inputs produce a comparably tight closure?}

We test a specific enumerated search space (Section~\ref{sec:space}) under two specific null models (Section~\ref{sec:mc}); the resulting tail probabilities apply only to that audited search space. The status of the analysis is exploratory with respect to the full enumeration and confirmatory only for claims explicitly fixed in the prior literature.

\paragraph{Terminology.} We report empirical tail probabilities ($p$-values) under specified null models. These are not severity assessments in the sense of Mayo~\citep{Mayo1996,MayoSpanos2006}: severity is the attained power computed under an alternative hypothesis and is a distinct quantity~\citep{CousinsLectures}. We use ``$p$-value'' exclusively.


\section{Search space}
\label{sec:space}

\subsection{Inputs}

$\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark masses are taken from FLAG~2024~\citep{FLAG2024} and PDG~2024~\citep{PDG2024}:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\toprule
Quark & Mass & $\sigma$ & Source \\
\midrule
$m_u(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $2.16$ MeV & $\pm 0.10$ & FLAG \\
$m_d(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $4.70$ MeV & $\pm 0.05$ & FLAG \\
$m_s(2\;\text{GeV})$ & $93.4$ MeV & $\pm 0.8$ & FLAG \\
$m_c(m_c)$ & $1280.7$ MeV & $\pm 1.3$ & FLAG \\
$m_b(m_b)$ & $4203$ MeV & $\pm 11$ & FLAG \\
$m_t(m_t)$ & $162.5$ GeV & $\pm 0.7$ & PDG \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Running uses four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ and full threshold matching.

\subsection{Evaluation scales and trial count}

For each quark we admit its self-scale and any SM particle mass within its perturbative running window. The top quark is held at its self-scale throughout (an operational convention for this scan, reflecting that $m_t$ enters the quoted FLAG/PDG value directly rather than via running, not a statement about the renormalization group). Light quarks $(u, d, s)$ have no perturbative self-scale and are referenced to $2$~GeV as the canonical FLAG scale.

The complete scale list is archived as \texttt{search\_space.json}~\citep{RepoMC}. The audited trial count, with the complete enumeration in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}, is
\begin{equation}
20\;\text{triples} \times 4\;\text{signs} \times (\text{variable scales per triple}) = 12{,}960\;\text{trials.}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Scope and defense of the search space}

The scale set is finite, discrete, and drawn from physically interpretable reference scales appearing in the literature: particle thresholds, SM particle masses, and the canonical FLAG reference at $2$~GeV. Two properties of this choice deserve emphasis.

First, the audit is \emph{non-exhaustive by construction}. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses). Each of these is an extension to which the same methodology could be applied.

Second, the audit is \emph{conservative with respect to scale freedom}. The $p$-values reported here apply only to the enumerated discrete search space; enlarging the scale set to arbitrary or continuous choices would increase the look-elsewhere burden and can only weaken significance claims. The discrete audit is therefore a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting of all conceivable scale freedom.


\section{Observed results}
\label{sec:results}

We write $\sigma_Q$ for the propagated uncertainty on $Q$ from the FLAG/PDG mass uncertainties and $\alpha_s$; it is computed by Monte Carlo resampling in Model~B (Section~\ref{sec:mc}), treating the inputs as Gaussian and uncorrelated in the baseline with correlation sensitivity tested in Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}. Because $Q$ is a nonlinear function of six masses and its sensitivity to each input differs across triples, $\sigma_Q$ is triple-specific; the representative SM-central value $\sigma_Q \approx 5.4 \times 10^{-4}$ is the magnitude that appears in the hit-count threshold and drift discussions below, and the per-triple values used in the Model~B $p$-value computation are those obtained by resampling within each trial. Of the 12{,}960 trials, 8 produce $|Q - 2/3| < \sigma_Q$, distributed across exactly three triples. The expected number of sub-$\sigma$ hits under the parametric bootstrap (Section~\ref{sec:mc}) is approximately~7, so the observed count is consistent with what perturbations of the actual masses would generate.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{llllcr}
\toprule
Triple & Scales & Signs & $Q$ & $|Q - 2/3|$ & $n\sigma$ \\
\midrule
$(c,b,t)$ & $c@m_\tau$, $b@$self, $t@$self & $(+,+,+)$ & $0.66672$ & $5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.09$ \\
$(s,c,b)$ & $s@2m_\tau$, $c@m_\tau$, $b@m_H$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66674$ & $6.9 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.13$ \\
$(u,s,c)$ & $u@(m_\tau{+}m_c)$, $s@m_c$, $c@m_b$ & $(-,+,+)$ & $0.66658$ & $9.0 \times 10^{-5}$ & $0.17$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Tightest closure per triple. The remaining 17 triples produce zero sub-$3\sigma$ hits across $9{,}648$ trials. Full results in the repository.}
\label{tab:hits}
\end{table}


\section{Two null models}
\label{sec:mc}

We test each candidate claim under two complementary null models. They answer different questions and are not interchangeable.

\subsection{Null Model A: generic random-spectrum reference null}

Six masses are drawn log-uniformly from $[2\;\text{MeV},\; 170\;\text{GeV}]$, sorted, and assigned to quark slots. Full four-loop CRunDec running is performed on every draw, with thresholds computed from the random masses themselves rather than from the SM values. The total is $100{,}000$ pseudo-experiments in the main run (an earlier $10{,}000$-experiment run gave values agreeing within $1$--$2$ binomial SE; both are reported in the repository for cross-checking). An initial implementation used a surrogate running scheme for speed; the surrogate did not reproduce the full-CRunDec result at the per-draw level when checked (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), and the numbers reported throughout this paper use the full-CRunDec rebuild.

\textbf{Question:} could a generic random spectrum produce this closure?

The log-uniform prior is chosen to span the SM quark mass range. It is not derived from a physical principle, and the choice of prior family is an analyst decision. Because the prior endpoints are chosen to span the SM quark mass range, Model~A tail probabilities should be read as relative rankings within the chosen class of SM-like spectra, not as absolute significance levels; reasonable alternative priors would shift the absolute values without a principled way to prefer one over another. Sensitivity to the prior is examined in Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity}.

\subsection{Null Model B: measurement-noise null around the observed spectrum}

Each quark mass is perturbed within its FLAG/PDG uncertainty (Gaussian, $1\sigma$, treated as uncorrelated in the baseline); $\alpha_s$ is perturbed within its uncertainty. Full four-loop CRunDec running is performed on every draw. The bootstrap perturbations are applied uniformly to all claims, including self-scale-only claims (an earlier draft implementation evaluated self-scale claims at the unperturbed central values, which produced trivially $p = 1$ for those claims; this has been corrected). The total is $2{,}000$ pseudo-experiments.

\textbf{Question:} is this closure distinguishable from measurement noise on the actual quark masses?

Model~B is a local-stability diagnostic: it tests whether the observed residual persists under perturbations of the current FLAG/PDG central values within their stated uncertainties. It is not a look-elsewhere correction against a broader reference class of spectra, which is the role of Model~A. Model~B's tail probability is approximately a monotone function of the ratio $r/\sigma_Q$ where $r = Q_{\text{obs}} - 2/3$: for relations with $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$ the tail probability is $\approx 0.5$ (the observed residual is many standard deviations from zero and bootstrap draws concentrate around it), and for relations with $|r| \ll \sigma_Q$ the tail probability is small (the observed residual is a small fraction of $\sigma_Q$). A low Model~B tail probability therefore restates the observed $r/\sigma_Q$ ratio and does not constitute independent evidence that a relation is non-accidental beyond what that ratio itself reports. We retain Model~B in the analysis because its sensitivity to correlation structure and perturbation magnitude (Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}) is a useful diagnostic on measurement-uncertainty assumptions, not because it carries inferential weight on its own.

The independence assumption is examined in Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}. Sensitivity to the magnitude of perturbations is tested at $0.5\times$, $1\times$, and $2\times$ the nominal uncertainties (Table~\ref{tab:bootstrap}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lcccc}
\toprule
Config & $\sigma$ mult & $p$(best) & MC median best & MC mean sub-$1\sigma$ \\
\midrule
Baseline & $1\times$ & $0.50$ & $4.94 \times 10^{-5}$ & $6.94$ \\
Tighter & $0.5\times$ & $0.53$ & $4.72 \times 10^{-5}$ & $7.57$ \\
Looser & $2\times$ & $0.47$ & $5.56 \times 10^{-5}$ & $6.77$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\caption{Parametric bootstrap sensitivity for the full search ($12{,}960$ trials). The $p$-values are stable across a $4\times$ range of assumed uncertainties.}
\label{tab:bootstrap}
\end{table}

\subsection{Interpretation}

Null Model~A asks whether the closure is unusual relative to a generic random spectrum. Pre-specified single-triple claims (those proposed in prior literature before the present audit; see Section~\ref{sec:discussion}) have smaller Model~A tail probabilities within the chosen prior class than the full search.

Null Model~B asks whether the closure is distinguishable from measurement noise on the actual masses. Most claims with $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$ return Model~B tail probabilities near $0.5$. The exception is the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ family of claims, for which $|r| \approx 0.09 \sigma_Q$ and the Model~B tail probability is accordingly small ($\approx 0.15$); this number restates the $r/\sigma_Q$ ratio and does not add evidential content.

The two models are answering different questions and should not be read as giving convergent evidence on a common inferential target. Model~A's tail probabilities are conditional on the random-spectrum prior and its hierarchy-preserving variants (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}); Model~B's tail probabilities are conditional on the bootstrap around current FLAG/PDG central values and are approximately determined by $r/\sigma_Q$. A claim's posture under each is reported separately and should be interpreted separately; the two cannot be combined into a single summary tail probability.

A claim with a low Model~A tail probability but a typical Model~B tail probability is unusual relative to the chosen random-spectrum prior class but has $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$. A claim with typical tail probabilities under both is fully consistent with noise under the chosen Model~A prior class and with measurement-noise perturbations around the observed spectrum. A claim with a low Model~A tail probability and a small Model~B tail probability is unusual relative to the chosen random-spectrum prior class and has $|r| \ll \sigma_Q$. Neither model, nor their combination, addresses whether a relation identified by this framework reflects underlying structure in nature; that is a separate question about physical meaningfulness that the present audit does not try to answer.


\section{Sensitivity of the null models}
\label{sec:robustness}

The two null models above each rest on assumptions a referee may reasonably question: that the running implementation is faithful, that the random-spectrum prior is a fair reference, that uncorrelated Gaussian perturbations capture the measurement-uncertainty structure, and that pseudo-experiments lost to numerical failure do not bias the result. We test each.

\subsection{Validation of surrogate running}
\label{sec:surrogate-validation}

An earlier implementation of Model~A used a surrogate running scheme, applying the same multiplicative ratios as the four-loop calculation but skipping the full CRunDec call per draw, for computational efficiency. To verify the surrogate, we recomputed a fixed-seed subsample of 500 Model~A pseudo-experiments using full four-loop CRunDec and compared per-draw best residuals across the $12{,}960$ trials.

The surrogate did not meet the validation criteria. The median fractional discrepancy in the per-draw best residual was $92\%$; the same trial was identified as best under both methods in only $0.2\%$ of draws; tail-probability confidence intervals at thresholds $\{10^{-3}, 10^{-4}, 10^{-5}\}$ did not overlap. The surrogate applied SM-derived multiplicative ratios to random spectra whose thresholds and flavor structure are different, and the approximation broke down per-draw.

We set aside the surrogate and rebuilt Model~A using full four-loop CRunDec on every draw (Section~\ref{sec:mc}, Null Model~A). Comparison of the rebuilt Model~A $p$-values to the surrogate values for the nine claims of Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} showed the qualitative ranking preserved: the same five claims meet $p < 0.05$, and the author-pre-specified $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim moved from $p = 0.005$ to $p = 0.002$. The agreement at the level of tail probabilities, despite the per-draw discrepancy, is fortunate but not relied upon: all numbers reported in Sections~\ref{sec:isolation} and~\ref{sec:discussion} use the full-CRunDec values.

\subsection{Hierarchy-preserving variant of Model A}
\label{sec:hierarchy-null}

