\label{tab:temporal-summary}
\end{table}

The $(c, b, t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim cannot yet be assessed by this criterion. It was identified post-hoc on the current FLAG/PDG central values~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt}, so its present small residual reflects the conditions under which it was selected and contains no information about whether the relation is exact. As $m_c$, $m_b$, and (to a smaller extent) $m_t$ are refined in subsequent FLAG and PDG releases, the residual will either converge toward zero (consistent with an exact relation) or drift away (consistent with selection on a particular set of central values). The drift thresholds in Table~\ref{tab:drift} provide a quantitative version of the same statement.


\subsection{A geometric extension treated separately}

A second class of Koide-type claim involves geometric constructions on the lepton triple rather than algebraic relations among quark masses. One such construction---the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, evaluated at the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$, compared against $m_s$---has been examined in a separate preprint~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}. Applying the framework of the present note to that construction is a worthwhile exercise but raises issues distinct from the quark-only search treated here, including a careful audit of geometric degrees of freedom and a parametric bootstrap centred on $m_s$ rather than on the lepton inputs. We defer that analysis to follow-up work and note here only that the same two-null-model framework is the appropriate tool.

\subsection{Limitations}

The search space is finite, discrete, and physically interpretable; it does not exhaust all conceivable Koide-type formulations. A continuous scale scan would inflate the trial count and the implied LEE penalty without bound, so the present discrete audit should be read as a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses).

Approximately one-third of random-spectrum Model~A draws fail in CRunDec because of pathological QCD configurations and are excluded. Median, KS, and analytic-1-loop crosscheck evidence (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}) all support the conjecture that excluded draws have stochastically larger best residuals, so the dropout exclusion biases reported tail probabilities upward (conservatively) by an amount of order $0.1$ in absolute tail probability for the full-search case. The failure set is identical under 4-loop and 2-loop running on the same random draws, so alternative loop orders within CRunDec do not give access to the dropped-draw values; the analytic 1-loop scheme has lower dropout ($\approx 13\%$) and provides the only direct comparison.

The 1/3/4/5-loop convergence study (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}) shows the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for \emph{running} claims to vary by $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across well-behaved loop orders, comparable in magnitude to the dropout systematic; \emph{self-scale} claims (Cao, Rivero, chain-no-run, 20-triple self) are perfectly stable across loop orders. A 2-loop run gave anomalous results whose origin is under investigation and is not used in the main analysis. All reported Model~A numbers use 4-loop running.

Sensitivity of the two null models is examined in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}, where the running implementation, the random-spectrum prior family, the assumption of uncorrelated FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and the loss-rate bias are each tested.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under the two tools audited here, at full search freedom the observed closures reproduce the median null residual, yielding tail probability $\approx 0.50$ under the 4-loop Model~A random-spectrum null and $\approx 0.50$ under the Model~B measurement-noise bootstrap. A matched-complexity knob-isolation test (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}, Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}) indicates that admitting non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the Model~A noise floor beyond what trial-count multiplicity alone produces. Sensitivity checks (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}) indicate that the full-search qualitative result is stable under the running implementation, under the choice of prior family within the tested range, and under plausible correlation structure in the FLAG/PDG uncertainties. Two characterized systematics apply to the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for running claims: a loop-order spread of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across orders 1, 3, 4, 5 on identical paired draws (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}; self-scale claims are stable), and a dropout-induced shift of order $0.1$ in the conservative direction, supported by both surrogate-distributional and analytic-1-loop crosschecks (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}). The qualitative ranking is preserved within fixed conditions on each.

Pre-specified single-triple claims occupy an intermediate position. The $(c,b,t)$ closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ has a baseline Model~A tail probability of $\approx 0.003$, $\approx 0.004$--$0.007$ under hierarchy-preserving variants, and a Model~B tail probability of $\approx 0.15$ that restates its observed residual ratio $|r|/\sigma_Q \approx 0.09$. The claim was published by the present author in~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} prior to the present audit, and the audit began as a sanity check on that claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space; the present analysis therefore provides a multiplicity-corrected restatement of a prior author claim under the chosen log-uniform prior class and 4-loop running, not an independent confirmation. The temporal trajectory of its residual across future FLAG/PDG releases (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}, Table~\ref{tab:drift}) is what a subsequent forward-looking evaluation would draw on.

The analysis, all code, all seeds, and the audited trial list are in the repository~\citep{RepoMC}.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} ($12{,}960$ trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, with thresholds computed from the input mass spectrum (SM values for Models~A and~B baseline; perturbed values for bootstrap variants; random values for random-spectrum draws). Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024.

Random-spectrum MC (Model~A): $100{,}000$ experiments in the main run (up from $10{,}000$ in earlier versions; values agree within $1$--$2$ SE), full CRunDec on every draw. Bootstrap MC (Model~B): $2{,}000$ experiments per correlation variant, full CRunDec on every draw, with perturbations applied uniformly to all claims including self-scale-only claims (an earlier draft implementation evaluated self-scale claims at unperturbed central values; this has been corrected and the corrected values are reported here). Surrogate validation: $500$ paired draws comparing surrogate to full CRunDec (the surrogate failed validation and was not used in the final analysis). Hierarchy-preserving null: $10{,}000$ experiments per variant. Matched-complexity knob-isolation test: $K = 1000$ random subsamples of size $N' \in \{40, 80, 160, 320, 640, 1280, 2560, 3240\}$ drawn from each of the signs-only ($80$), running-only ($3{,}240$), and full-search ($12{,}960$) trial pools. Loop-order convergence study: $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws at 1-, 3-, 4-, and 5-loop CRunDec (an additional 2-loop run gave anomalous results under investigation and is not used in the main analysis). Analytic 1-loop crosscheck: pure-Python closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching, $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws ($13.4\%$ dropout vs.\ $32.7\%$ for full CRunDec). Loss-bias check: distribution comparison on $3{,}269$ dropped draws against $6{,}731$ retained draws under surrogate running. All seeds documented in the repository.


